        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>June 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>—</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I heard from the Bank this morning that the <hi rend="superscript">£</hi>201 . 3<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> . 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> has been received from you, for which &amp; your note of the 7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>—I am much obliged.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>It is of course very satisfactory to me, to hear that you think yourself justified in giving notice to the Tenant<ref target="#foot.f2"/> that the whole rent must be paid next half.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With my thanks | Pray believe me | Dear Sir | Yours sincerely | C. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> J. Higgins Esq<hi rend="superscript">e</hi></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD recorded the receipt of £206 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on 10 June 1853 in his Classed account book (Down House MS). The sum mentioned in the letter is the Beesby rent less a £5 donation to Beesby School.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The Beesby Farm tenant was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2117.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Hardy</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1432.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Higgins, 7 June 1851</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In 1850 CD had agreed to a reduction of 15% in rent on the Beesby Farm because of the slump in agricultural prices. From May 1850 to June 1853 the accounts show a reduction of that amount. The payment in June 1853 of £206 3<hi rend="italic">s.</hi> 2<hi rend="italic">d.</hi> represented a reduction of nearly 8<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula>%. In December 1853 the full payment of £225 was made.</note>
        </div>        
            
